{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_013gx6y3H2J4YAUKuxXvu65o","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this problem, I need to evaluate $I = \\int_0^\\infty t^{-1/2} e^{-1985(t + 1/t)}\\, dt$.\n\n**Substitution $t = u^2$:** Then $dt = 2u\\,du$ and $t^{-1/2} = 1/u$, giving\n$$I = 2\\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du, \\quad a = 1985.$$\n\nLet $J = \\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du$, so $I = 2J$.\n\n**Symmetry trick:** Sub $w = 1/u$ (so $du = -dw/w^2$) in $J$:\n$$J = \\int_0^\\infty \\frac{1}{w^2}\\, e^{-a(w^2 + 1/w^2)}\\,dw.$$\n\nAveraging the two expressions for $J$:\n$$2J = \\int_0^\\infty \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{u^2}\\right) e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du.$$\n\n**Substitution $v = u - 1/u$:** Then $dv = (1 + 1/u^2)\\,du$, and $u^2 + 1/u^2 = v^2 + 2$. As $u: 0 \\to \\infty$, $v: -\\infty \\to \\infty$.\n$$2J = e^{-2a}\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty e^{-av^2}\\,dv = e^{-2a}\\sqrt{\\pi/a}.$$\n\nSo $I = 2J = e^{-2a}\\sqrt{\\pi/a} = \\sqrt{\\pi/1985}\\, e^{-3970}$.\n\nANSWER: $\\sqrt{\\pi/1985}\\, e^{-3970}$\nCONFIDENCE: high"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":556,"cache_read_input_tokens":19543,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":556},"output_tokens":60,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f8dac5ac-b0b8-4ea5-a084-586b1a2d210b","uuid":"c4a51522-665e-4e48-afcd-b52124e006da","request_id":"req_011CbDQLSMynpZge3WhRciK7"}
